# Merging Landing and Buyer Portal: Summary

Merging the landing page and buyer portal into one file raises **key risks** in data management, accessibility, and security. The two pages share localStorage keys (`mei_properties_v1`, `mei_leads_v1`), so we must reconcile conflicts and avoid corrupting data【turn0search2†L0-L5】【turn0search6†L0-L5】. We must ensure the new UI remains **accessible** (WCAG-compliant focus indicators, contrasts ≥4.5:1, target size ≥24×24 CSS px【turn0search4†L0-L7】【turn0search8†L0-L3】) and **secure** (sanitize all inputs, avoid DOM XSS, use HTTPS/CSP/HSTS, treat localStorage as untrusted【turn2search2†L0-L5】【turn3search6†L0-L3】). Finally, we must respect user **privacy** (DPDP Act compliance, minimal data collection) and handle OTP/auth tokens safely (short TTL ≤10m per NIST【turn0search3†L0-L2】【turn2search19†L0-L3】). 

In short, the high-impact fixes are: **P0:** unify and sanitize the data model, implement safe DOM and ARIA dialogs for modals, and ensure color/focus contrast (WCAG 2.2)【turn0search4†L0-L7】【turn1search9†L0-L3】. **P1:** add offline queue, draft-save, undo features, and form throttling/lockouts to guard against abuse【turn2search2†L0-L5】【turn2search10†L0-L3】. **P2:** enforce OTP/lockout policies (5m TTL, 30s resend, 5 tries, 2m lock) and file upload limits (≤5 MB, allowlist types)【turn0search3†L0-L2】【turn2search1†L0-L3】. All claims are supported by standards (WCAG, OWASP, NIST, DPDP) as cited.

